{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/retinal-detachment/background-information/risk-factors/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"85ba124b-cb79-55bf-970f-0ad15fc8f02d","slug":"risk-factors","fullItemName":"Risk factors","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 965f016c-1648-4ae2-a1e4-a61fe643376c --><h2>What are the risk factors?</h2><!-- end field 965f016c-1648-4ae2-a1e4-a61fe643376c -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 380d8ef1-7669-47f5-8ffe-0e5bc672129b --><!-- begin field 3c44c2d1-96e9-4c7f-beae-0f4b7019fb85 --><p><strong>Risk factors for retinal detachment vary depending on the underlying type and site of detachment, and include:</strong></p><ul><li>Myopia (short-sightedness) — this increases the risk of <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/background-information/definition/\">posterior vitreous detachment</a>, and the peripheral retina may be thinned and more likely to tear.</li><li>Family history of retinal break or detachment — there may be a tendency towards inherited myopia or degenerative retinal lesions.</li><li>Previous history of retinal break or detachment in this eye or the other eye — about 1 in 8 people with retinal detachment develop subsequent detachment in the contralateral eye.</li><li>Eye trauma (especially blunt trauma, for example due to boxing) — there may be a latent period of several months to years before retinal detachment is detected. In older children, most cases of retinal detachment are secondary to a history of trauma.</li><li>Previous cataract surgery — this accelerates posterior vitreous detachment.<ul><li>Retinal detachment occurs in about 1% of people in the weeks to years after cataract surgery, almost nine times higher than expected.</li><li>Previous complicated cataract surgery substantially increases the risk of subsequent retinal detachment.</li><li>See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/cataracts/\">Cataracts</a> for more information.</li></ul></li><li>Proliferative diabetic retinopathy — due to chronic traction from scars on the retinal surface.<ul><li>See the CKS topics on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/diabetes-type-1/\">Diabetes - type 1</a> and <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/diabetes-type-2/\">Diabetes - type 2</a> for more information.</li></ul></li><li>Inflammatory conditions (for example uveitis and scleritis) — these may predispose to exudative retinal detachment.<ul><li>See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/uveitis/\">Uveitis</a> for more information.</li></ul></li><li>Malignancy (for example choroidal melanoma or ocular metastasis) — predisposes to exudative retinal detachment.</li><li>Congenital eye diseases, such as glaucoma, cataract, or retinopathy of prematurity.<ul><li>See the CKS topics on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/glaucoma/\">Glaucoma</a> and <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/cataracts/\">Cataracts</a> for more information.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Gariano and Kim, 2004</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Go et al, 2005</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Bhagat, 2007</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Kang and Luff, 2008</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Royal College of Ophthalmologists, 2010</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Gelston, 2013a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Yanoff, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Khan, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Shah, 2014</a>]</p><!-- end field 3c44c2d1-96e9-4c7f-beae-0f4b7019fb85 --><!-- end item 380d8ef1-7669-47f5-8ffe-0e5bc672129b -->","topic":{"id":"9be2cb0d-8648-5694-a09c-292ca1ced19e","topicId":"e3f75bdf-a207-4239-9931-367d38a9b7d6","topicName":"Retinal detachment","slug":"retinal-detachment","lastRevised":"Last revised in August 2019","chapters":[{"id":"842ff08c-c002-50cd-bab2-348ba3e67be0","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"98f29b98-1286-5c16-a606-4cd90cc70465","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"873d5520-2d22-5b9d-bd04-6d9112dc82ee","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"3b54abb3-d415-51e3-996b-1d6e3bcc3d3b","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"0aa87cea-a601-54db-9dcb-ec3117e7098a","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"dbe4b4fd-c326-5686-bd9a-71905fc13c76","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"9f38c5e9-5edd-56fa-a740-0d19004a69af","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"5960233a-64c2-5a35-95ea-6a44ae788808","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"e506d9ce-54a0-57f2-b4d1-49bb28e3d283","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"0ce8a869-7cf6-588c-b609-d5a90fa6adf0","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"a1808dfe-2608-5274-a314-61a4054cb431","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"6148c790-0603-5594-9e2f-9d1a8bdaab45","slug":"nice-quality-st